If those quotes have changed and you also want to match the encoded version you could use an [alternation](https://www.regular-expressions.info/alternation.html) to match either one of them in a capturing group and then use a [backreference](https://www.regular-expressions.info/backref.html) `\1` for the same match as the accompanying closing match.

Your value is in the second capturing group as the first group is used for the backreference.

    \[yu_TOC title=(&quot;|&amp;#8221;)(.*?)\1\s*\]

[Regex demo](https://regex101.com/r/uCzm3N/1) | [Php demo](https://3v4l.org/oY8aC)

**Note** that you don&#39;t have to escape `&quot;`

For example

    $content = [&quot;[yu_TOC title=&amp;#8221;Short Stories&amp;#8221;]&lt;/p&gt;&quot;];
    preg_match(&#39;/\[yu_TOC title=(&quot;|&amp;#8221;)(.*?)\1\s*\]/&#39;, $content[0], $matchedTitle);
    print_r($matchedTitle);

Output

    Array
    (
        [0] =&gt; [yu_TOC title=&amp;#8221;Short Stories&amp;#8221;]
        [1] =&gt; &amp;#8221;
        [2] =&gt; Short Stories
    )

This:

    const { state = {} } = this.$store;

is [*destructuring assignment*][1] with a *default value* if the source (`this.$store`) either doesn&#39;t have the property `state` or has it but with the value `undefined`. The result will be that `state` will have the value of `this.$store.state` if that property exists and doesn&#39;t have the value `undefined`, or will have a new blank object if the property doesn&#39;t exist or has the value `undefined`.

Example (using a string instead of an object, but it&#39;s the same principal):

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const obj1 = {};
    const { a = &quot;default&quot; } = obj1;
    console.log(a);        // &quot;default&quot;

    const obj2 = {
        b: &quot;value from obj2&quot;
    };
    const { b = &quot;default&quot; } = obj2;
    console.log(b);        // &quot;value from obj2&quot;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Destructuring_assignment#Object_destructuring

